<subSubSection id="06FF8A367A88B0547190583C5B8458D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="9A0C2FEEBB3BFFFE982DDA313CFAC2CA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7FBB34C841B78DD4B79B336B963E2697" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Due to their simple morphology, there is much confusion in the taxonomic literature dealing with 
<taxonomicName id="DBA1560C2040871C7EDEC2C8E6FBD1E5" family="Opheliidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Opheliidae</taxonomicName>
, and many species and genera are currently considered invalid (Read and Fauchald 2018c). Useful recent studies clarifying some of the confusion are 
<bibRefCitation id="05DB5D1F18A209C639C20411FC9CFAEE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" author="Kongsrud, JA" journalOrPublisher="Italian Journal of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="95 - 111" refId="B54" refString="Kongsrud, JA, Bakken, T, Oug, E, 2011. Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov. Italian Journal of Zoology 78: 95 - 111" title="Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" volume="78" year="2011">Kongsrud et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="6BAC71CEA66F0F4BE15D02D6C97220BC" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-011-0046-2" author="Parapar, J" journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B74" refString="Parapar, J, Moreira, J, Helgason, GV, 2011. .https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-011-0046-2" url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13127-011-0046-2" year="2011">Parapar et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
based on material collected from North-East Atlantic. It would appear that several previous descriptions were based on what are in fact different, if morphologically very similar, species. Characters such as the shape of the prostomium and associated palpode are often reported in descriptions and used to distinguish species, but the UKSR material showed that the shape in preserved specimens may be variable and the shape and size of the associated palpode can also vary with preservation. Additionally, the shape of the prostomium in live specimens can be of different shape to that observed in preserved specimens (L. Neal pers. obs.) and thus this character might not be useful. Mouth structures in opheliids are rarely observed and reported but considered important by some authors (
<bibRefCitation id="417E1553A64F049C362F75CE6C3D6E26" author="Tzetlin, A" journalOrPublisher="Zoosymposia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="415 - 427" refId="B96" refString="Tzetlin, A, Zhadan, A, 2009. Morphological variation of axial non-muscular proboscis types in the Polychaeta. Zoosymposia 2: 415 - 427" title="Morphological variation of axial non-muscular proboscis types in the Polychaeta." volume="2" year="2009">Tzetlin and Zhadan 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The number of chaetigers in a specimen has been deemed as a useful character by e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="A1FF610F30C1E636ED12FA1B0CBAA925" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" author="Kongsrud, JA" journalOrPublisher="Italian Journal of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="95 - 111" refId="B54" refString="Kongsrud, JA, Bakken, T, Oug, E, 2011. Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov. Italian Journal of Zoology 78: 95 - 111" title="Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" volume="78" year="2011">Kongsrud et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="DFAE920BD42FE6C4BD6FD95B14A00136" author="Blake, JA" journalOrPublisher="Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History, Santa Barbara, California" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="145 - 168" refId="B8" refString="Blake, JA, 2000b. Family Opheliidae Malmgren, 1867. Taxonomic Atlas of the Benthic Fauna of the Santa Maria Basin and the Western Santa Barbara Channel. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History, Santa Barbara, California 7: 145 - 168" title="Family Opheliidae Malmgren, 1867. Taxonomic Atlas of the Benthic Fauna of the Santa Maria Basin and the Western Santa Barbara Channel." volume="7" year="2000 b">Blake (2000b)</bibRefCitation>
. The chaetae of the opheliids are relatively uniform smooth capillaries of limited taxonomical importance. However, Sarda et al. (2009) reported the presence of hirsute capillaries in 
<taxonomicName id="FB47F456567AE2A0314B57B91FFD5062" class="Polychaeta" family="Opheliidae" genus="Ophelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophelina margaleffi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="margaleffi">
<emphasis id="986D8CC6352B8D6908D81595B98C57E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophelina margaleffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sarda et al., 2009 observed under SEM. Opheliid branchiae are very fragile structures which are easily lost and thus their distribution and number can be difficult to observe. 
<bibRefCitation id="C8F822BA35A4EDBFEECC18A9713BFDE1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" author="Kongsrud, JA" journalOrPublisher="Italian Journal of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="95 - 111" refId="B54" refString="Kongsrud, JA, Bakken, T, Oug, E, 2011. Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov. Italian Journal of Zoology 78: 95 - 111" title="Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" volume="78" year="2011">Kongsrud et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
illustrated the importance of examining a relatively large number of specimens in order to correctly establish the characters of these structures. The anal tube is also a very fragile structure that is easily lost, and true absence is difficult to distinguish from loss due to damage. 
<bibRefCitation id="D2C2A4A70DAA1B12227C329B68E8B397" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" author="Kongsrud, JA" journalOrPublisher="Italian Journal of Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="95 - 111" refId="B54" refString="Kongsrud, JA, Bakken, T, Oug, E, 2011. Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov. Italian Journal of Zoology 78: 95 - 111" title="Deep-water species of the genus Ophelina (Annelida, Opheliidae) in the Nordic Seas, with the description of Ophelinabrattegardi sp. nov." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/11250003.2011.606658" volume="78" year="2011">Kongsrud et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
again illustrated the importance of examining a relatively large number of specimens in order to correctly establish the presence and form of this structure.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F62C7F61456028496D4657222528B697" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Unfortunately, the ABYSSLINE material provides very few specimens (often just one) per species, which complicates the morphological interpretation. Nevertheless, in combination with DNA data, we believe it is important to provide the currently best possible morphology, which can be amended as more and better-preserved examples become available in the future. As a result, only 8 out of 15 opheliid species found in the ABYSSLINE material are here formally described. Morphologically, the ABYSSLINE material can be assigned to two known genera, 
<taxonomicName id="D7D104625B77931CE87DDF3A7AA0FC4F" class="Polychaeta" family="Opheliidae" genus="Ammotrypanella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ammotrypanella" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FCEB0277F84E7274803878322514DEC0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ammotrypanella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
McIntosh, 1878 and 
<taxonomicName id="343740E7F3CAA4FC1B2F003DFCC70C9E" class="Polychaeta" family="Opheliidae" genus="Ophelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophelina" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2F4DEAA6E75CF91B3E3F93B65D8650D9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophelina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="20A15D58C18E159399B2FB24F842BD30" originalValue="Ã–rsted">Oersted</normalizedToken>
, 1843.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
